00:43:06.464 --> 00:43:08.489
Long live the King!

499
00:43:09.133 --> 00:43:11.101
Long live the King!
Long live the King!

500
00:43:11.535 --> 00:43:13.464
Long live the King!
Long live the King!

501
00:43:14.005 --> 00:43:15.597
Rise.

502
00:43:20.278 --> 00:43:21.738
You.. .

503
00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:24.907
I don't know you.

504
00:43:25.383 --> 00:43:28.311
Robert Loxley, Sire,
of Nottingham.

505
00:43:29.053 --> 00:43:30.920
Welcome then.

506
00:43:31.422 --> 00:43:34.115
And how did my brother die?

507
00:43:34.859 --> 00:43:37.020
In battle, Your Majesty,
as was his way.

508
00:43:38.329 --> 00:43:40.228
As was his way.

509
00:43:40.531 --> 00:43:41.691
You deserve a reward.. .

510
00:43:41.766 --> 00:43:42.824
<font color="#ff80ff">ALLAN:</font> Let's get the horses.

511
00:43:42.900 --> 00:43:44.890
.. .for bringing home the news.

512
00:43:46.604 --> 00:43:47.764
Kneel.

513
00:43:54.946 --> 00:43:56.675
Did you say you were from Nottingham?

514
00:43:58.115 --> 00:43:59.507
Yes.

515
00:44:01.852 --> 00:44:04.313
Your father, Sir Walter,

516
00:44:05.489 --> 00:44:07.454
owes tax to the crown.

517
00:44:10.661 --> 00:44:11.889
My crown.

518
00:44:11.963 --> 00:44:14.329
Tell him it's bloody expensive
running a country

519
00:44:14.398 --> 00:44:16.832
and everyone's got
to pay their way.

520
00:44:16.901 --> 00:44:19.466
We'll start with this.

521
00:44:20.471 --> 00:44:24.036
Make way for the King!
Make way!

522
00:44:24.075 --> 00:44:25.269
Your Majesty.

523
00:44:25.343 --> 00:44:28.408
Make way for the King!

524
00:44:32.683 --> 00:44:34.712
Make way!
Godfrey.

525
00:44:35.319 --> 00:44:38.481
Godfrey, my friend.
It's so good to see you.

526
00:44:38.556 --> 00:44:41.490
How were your travels?
Good, Sire.

527
00:44:41.692 --> 00:44:44.052
What happened to your face?

528
00:44:44.095 --> 00:44:47.224
A hunting accident.
It's nothing.

529
00:44:47.231 --> 00:44:48.926
Frightening.
Your Majesty.

530
00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:53.292
Call it a dueling scar.
The ladies will love you all the more.

531
00:44:53.337 --> 00:44:55.498
I bow to your knowledge
of the ladies, Sire.

532
00:44:59.910 --> 00:45:02.539
You can get up now.

533
00:45:10.154 --> 00:45:12.719
<font color="#ff80ff">MARSHAL: </font>Sir Robert.

534
00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:20.418
You will know of me, perhaps.
I'm William Marshal.

535
00:45:20.698 --> 00:45:23.931
Your father and I were
young men together.

536
00:45:23.934 --> 00:45:28.602
Tell him I'm coming to visit him soon,
on spring's first black night.

537
00:45:29.940 --> 00:45:32.140
I may have need of him.

538
00:45:32.209 --> 00:45:34.774
I will. I'll tell him.

539
00:45:36.781 --> 00:45:41.617
Whoever he is and whatever he is,
he knows too much.

540
00:45:43.187 --> 00:45:46.011
Get rid of him.

541
00:45:57.902 --> 00:46:00.567
Come on, let's follow.

542
00:46:28.199 --> 00:46:30.791
<font color="#ff80ff">(RUSTLING)</font>

543
00:46:46.183 --> 00:46:49.116
<font color="#ff80ff">(DISTANT CALLING)</font>

544
00:47:02.967 --> 00:47:04.662
Forfeit what you got.

545
00:47:04.735 --> 00:47:07.895
Victuals, coin, clothing

546
00:47:07.905 --> 00:47:09.672
or your life.

547
00:47:09.707 --> 00:47:11.197
<font color="#ff80ff">(COUGHING)</font>

548
00:47:11.275 --> 00:47:14.335
Thomas Cooper.

549
00:47:14.612 --> 00:47:16.511
ls that you?

550
00:47:20.317 --> 00:47:22.714
Are you sick, Thomas?

551
00:47:22.953 --> 00:47:25.077
We're all sick.

552
00:47:25.589 --> 00:47:28.456
Where are the rest of you?
Don't tell her.

553
00:47:28.526 --> 00:47:29.959
Loop will be angry.

554
00:47:30.027 --> 00:47:31.892
No, it's your mother
who's going to be angry.

555
00:47:31.962 --> 00:47:35.989
Now, either you come with me,
or I come with you.

556
00:47:36.066 --> 00:47:38.031
You choose.

557
00:47:38.669 --> 00:47:42.360
Well, come on then.
Where are they?

558
00:47:42.439 --> 00:47:44.270
Answer me.

559
00:48:32.590 --> 00:48:35.618
4 men, 5 horses, one gray.

560
00:48:35.659 --> 00:48:39.089
Have you seen them?
That way.

561
00:48:44.501 --> 00:48:48.597
The living king of sermons

562
00:48:48.672 --> 00:48:51.832
Was delivered from his evil

563
00:48:52.276 --> 00:48:55.211
But he couldn't talk his last

564
00:48:55.279 --> 00:48:58.777
Because God took out his throat

565
00:48:58.782 --> 00:49:02.309
God's crossbow took out his throat

566
00:49:02.386 --> 00:49:06.287
By Christ! Can you not
sing a happy tune?

567
00:49:06.290 --> 00:49:11.853
Sing a foot-stomper about adventure
and daring and courage.

568
00:49:11.929 --> 00:49:16.121
No. Sing something about a woman.

569
00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:18.127
A large woman.

570
00:49:18.202 --> 00:49:21.865
Fancy army, darling
I loves you all to bits

571
00:49:21.939 --> 00:49:25.204
I'll climb up to your chamber
And under your mountainous...

572
00:49:25.276 --> 00:49:28.470
Right. I'm done.
The money's divided.

573
00:49:28.746 --> 00:49:30.679
And so should we be.

574
00:49:30.714 --> 00:49:32.838
Where will you go?

575
00:49:34.652 --> 00:49:37.644
I think something is owed
for this good fortune,

576
00:49:37.721 --> 00:49:39.211
and I mean to pay it back.

577
00:49:39.290 --> 00:49:41.484
How so?

578
00:49:41.925 --> 00:49:45.922
The inscription on the sword,
it taunts my memory.

579
00:49:45.996 --> 00:49:49.331
Maybe it's just my imagination,
I don't know.

580
00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:52.494
But I intend to take that
sword back to its owner

581
00:49:52.569 --> 00:49:54.298
and fulfill the request
of his dying son.

582
00:49:54.371 --> 00:49:56.065
<font color="#ff80ff">WILL:</font> Are you mad?

583
00:49:56.106 --> 00:49:58.165
You just said we were
in danger, Robin.

584
00:49:58.242 --> 00:50:01.977
Now you choose to step
back in to harm's way?

585
00:50:02.012 --> 00:50:04.207
They're bound to go
there and find you.

586
00:50:04.281 --> 00:50:09.342
We can't repay our good luck
with bad grace. lt invites darkness.

587
00:50:13.357 --> 00:50:15.452
I'm going with you.
And I, Robin.

588
00:50:15.492 --> 00:50:17.254
Yes. No.

589
00:50:18.062 --> 00:50:20.121
Tonight is our last in company.

590
00:50:20.197 --> 00:50:24.066
Tomorrow, we go
our separate ways.

591
00:50:24.868 --> 00:50:28.401
Pack up your share.
We eat and sleep.

592
00:50:28.405 --> 00:50:31.605
Will, you're on first watch.

593
00:50:40.451 --> 00:50:43.141
<font color="#ff80ff">(SNORING)</font>

594
00:51:17.221 --> 00:51:20.379
<font color="#ff80ff">(MIMICS ANIMAL CALLING)</font>

595
00:51:33.003 --> 00:51:34.727
Will.

596
00:52:04.435 --> 00:52:06.727
Watch your step!

597
00:52:06.970 --> 00:52:09.528
One of them got away.

598
00:52:09.573 --> 00:52:13.198
Bastards! They've stolen my fortune.

599
00:52:13.577 --> 00:52:15.875
Richard's army is coming home.

600
00:52:15.946 --> 00:52:19.143
It costs money to keep it together.
Marshal, you speak for the money.

601
00:52:19.216 --> 00:52:20.376
I do, Sire.

602
00:52:20.451 --> 00:52:24.709
But to disband the army
could cost more than to keep it.

603
00:52:27.224 --> 00:52:31.558
King Richard's campaigns were costly.
And the expected returns.. .

604
00:52:31.628 --> 00:52:34.592
What is that to me, Marshal?

605
00:52:34.665 --> 00:52:38.056
My brother's troubles are over!

606
00:52:38.402 --> 00:52:40.729
They're over!

607
00:52:42.272 --> 00:52:44.164
Clear the room.

608
00:52:55.486 --> 00:52:58.080
So.. . Taxation.

609
00:52:58.155 --> 00:52:59.349
Taxation?

610
00:52:59.423 --> 00:53:04.092
Milking a dry udder gets you nothing
but kicked off the milking stool.

611
00:53:04.127 --> 00:53:05.992
Mother, spare me your
farmyard memories.

612
00:53:06.063 --> 00:53:08.725
You have none and
I don't understand them.

613
00:53:08.799 --> 00:53:12.562
These are difficult times.
We can buy time.

614
00:53:12.569 --> 00:53:15.331
I can send envoys
to secure loans.

615
00:53:15.372 --> 00:53:18.598
There are money chests from Sicily to
Normandy if you know where to look.

616
00:53:18.642 --> 00:53:20.837
Cap-in-hand to moneylenders?

617
00:53:20.878 --> 00:53:22.943
Your master's a king.

618
00:53:22.946 --> 00:53:25.278
The crown is owed money at home.

619
00:53:25.349 --> 00:53:30.581
The northern barons plead poverty,
but that's always been the song of rich men.

620
00:53:30.621 --> 00:53:33.786
So, what's to be done?

621
00:53:48.305 --> 00:53:51.731
Give me leave, Sire, to go north
with a company of mounted men.

622
00:53:51.808 --> 00:53:54.699
I'll have the merchants and
landowners fill your coffers

623
00:53:54.711 --> 00:53:56.338
or their coffins.

624
00:53:56.413 --> 00:53:58.813
Englishmen killing Englishmen.

625
00:53:58.882 --> 00:54:02.442
No man loyal to the crown
has anything to fear.

626
00:54:02.519 --> 00:54:08.413
And loyalty means paying your
share in the defense of the realm.

627
00:54:08.725 --> 00:54:10.749
That's well said.

628
00:54:11.261 --> 00:54:13.756
Don't you think, Marshal?

629
00:54:14.331 --> 00:54:15.491
Mother?

630
00:54:15.566 --> 00:54:20.863
Richard commanded loyalty
not by threats but by example.

631
00:54:20.871 --> 00:54:24.231
Mother, your sainted
son was an imbecile.

632
00:54:24.308 --> 00:54:29.971
And you supported his every folly
from here to Jerusalem and back.

633
00:54:30.047 --> 00:54:33.175
Yes, you worshipped him

634
00:54:33.250 --> 00:54:37.352
when the warrior lost territories
hard won by his father.

635
00:54:37.354 --> 00:54:39.447
You kissed his picture

636
00:54:39.523 --> 00:54:42.788
while England had to pay
four years' revenue

637
00:54:42.859 --> 00:54:44.554
to ransom him when
he was captured.

638
00:54:44.628 --> 00:54:47.119
You are just as much
to blame as anyone

639
00:54:47.197 --> 00:54:51.327
for the wreckage which
is my inheritance.

640
00:55:03.580 --> 00:55:07.310
I broke her skin more
than she did mine.

641
00:55:13.857 --> 00:55:15.722
Chancellor.

642
00:55:21.465 --> 00:55:23.093
Marshal,

643
00:55:24.468 --> 00:55:29.497
you served my brother faithfully
and my father before him.

644
00:55:29.673 --> 00:55:32.640
I think you've spent enough
time with my family

645
00:55:32.643 --> 00:55:35.903
and no doubt, would like
to spend more with your own.

646
00:55:37.180 --> 00:55:40.180
Therefore and with regret,

647
00:55:40.183 --> 00:55:45.350
I accept your resignation of all
your offices and matters of state.

648
00:55:46.957 --> 00:55:49.119
The ring.

649
00:55:56.266 --> 00:55:58.333
Your Majesty.

650
00:56:16.853 --> 00:56:22.016
Choose carefully, Godfrey, the spot
where you would place your dagger.

651
00:56:29.433 --> 00:56:32.958
For I will choose carefully as well.

652
00:56:55.258 --> 00:56:58.382
Open the gates!

653
00:57:32.896 --> 00:57:34.861
Nottingham.

654
00:57:35.532 --> 00:57:38.730
Is this your people, Robin?
I don't know. Might be.

655
00:57:38.769 --> 00:57:42.170
They don't look much,
these Middle Englanders.

656
00:57:42.239 --> 00:57:44.901
Well, they've been keeping your lot
in place easy enough, haven't they?

657
00:57:44.975 --> 00:57:48.208
I hear that you Welsh boys,
you live on leeks.

658
00:57:48.211 --> 00:57:51.079
You co-habit with sheep.

659
00:57:51.081 --> 00:57:52.673
<font color="#ff80ff">(MIMICS SHEEP BLEATING)</font>

660
00:57:52.749 --> 00:57:54.614
Bloody Scottish mule.

661
00:57:54.684 --> 00:57:56.117
<font color="#ff80ff">(SHUSHING)</font>

662
00:57:56.186 --> 00:57:59.644
You wouldn't want to annoy a bee
hive with your noise, would you?

663
00:57:59.723 --> 00:58:01.857
Your swords would be
no good then, gentlemen.

664
00:58:01.925 --> 00:58:04.217
You're the town beekeeper?

665
00:58:04.227 --> 00:58:07.594
Bless you, no. I'm the friar.
Tuck's the name.

666
00:58:07.664 --> 00:58:11.800
Well, Friar Tuck, can you tell me
where I might find Sir Walter Loxley?

667
00:58:11.868 --> 00:58:14.431
If he's not up at Peper Harow.. .

668
00:58:16.239 --> 00:58:18.401
How long will your business take?

669
00:58:22.612 --> 00:58:24.336
Stay safe.

670
00:58:24.381 --> 00:58:26.643
God be with you all.

671
00:58:32.856 --> 00:58:33.982
That's it?

672
00:58:34.057 --> 00:58:36.190
After 10 years?

673
00:58:37.027 --> 00:58:39.996
Good Friar, where
can a man get, well,

674
00:58:40.063 --> 00:58:42.422
moderately insensible
on a drink around here?

675
00:58:42.499 --> 00:58:46.962
Allan, he's a man of the cloth.
I'm sorry, Friar.

676
00:58:46.970 --> 00:58:49.865
Have you coin?
I have coin.

677
00:58:49.873 --> 00:58:52.072
Two pieces.

678
00:58:52.075 --> 00:58:53.667
Each.

679
00:58:54.344 --> 00:58:58.679
Have you tried the honey
liquor we call mead?

680
00:58:59.316 --> 00:59:01.383
Come with me.

681
00:59:01.451 --> 00:59:05.381
Gives a man a halo,
does mead.

682
00:59:35.385 --> 00:59:36.443
Girl.

683
00:59:36.519 --> 00:59:40.210
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCOFFlNG)</font> Girl?

684
00:59:43.059 --> 00:59:46.326
Either you're going blind
or you're looking for charity.

685
00:59:46.396 --> 00:59:48.387
Are you the keeper of this house?

686
00:59:48.465 --> 00:59:51.060
In a manner of speaking, yes.

687
00:59:51.067 --> 00:59:54.364
I wish to see Sir Walter Loxley.

688
00:59:55.238 --> 00:59:57.964
And you are?
Robin Longstride.

689
00:59:58.041 --> 01:00:00.509
Plain Robin Longstride?
No Sir?

690
01:00:00.510 --> 01:00:03.069
No, ma'am. No Sir.

691
01:00:06.316 --> 01:00:08.581
Are you here about the tax?

692
01:00:08.585 --> 01:00:12.919
No, I'm here to bring him his
sword. His son's dead.

693
01:00:15.158 --> 01:00:16.920
This way.

694
01:00:38.348 --> 01:00:41.413
He'll take your horse.

695
01:00:49.559 --> 01:00:51.751
<font color="#ff80ff">(SIGHS)</font>

696
01:00:52.128 --> 01:00:54.022
<font color="#ff80ff">WALTER:</font> Marion!

697
01:00:54.064 --> 01:00:55.458
Marion!

698
01:00:55.532 --> 01:00:58.527
Maggie, where is she?

699
01:00:58.969 --> 01:01:00.527
Ma'am, Sir Walter calls for you.

700
01:01:00.603 --> 01:01:03.503
I know, Margaret.
I can hear him.

701
01:01:03.540 --> 01:01:06.731
Tell him we have a guest.

702
01:01:14.884 --> 01:01:19.020
I'm Marion Loxley.
Robert's wife.

703
01:01:22.592 --> 01:01:25.584
My Lady, I owe you an apology.
lf I'd have known.. .

704
01:01:25.662 --> 01:01:29.927
Bad news is bad news
no matter how it comes.

705
01:01:30.233 --> 01:01:35.470
Indeed, I owe you thanks for taking
the time to deliver it here yourself.

706
01:01:35.472 --> 01:01:38.663
Did you fight alongside
my husband?

707
01:01:39.642 --> 01:01:41.000
Yes.

708
01:01:42.112 --> 01:01:44.306
Did he die well?

709
01:01:47.550 --> 01:01:49.081
In an ambush, ma'am.

710
01:01:49.152 --> 01:01:52.685
He was the man chosen to
bring home Richard's crown.

711
01:01:52.722 --> 01:01:55.481
Marion, who is here?

712
01:01:56.159 --> 01:01:58.488
A traveler, Walter.

713
01:02:03.466 --> 01:02:05.934
This news will go
very hard on him.

714
01:02:06.002 --> 01:02:08.694
<font color="#ff80ff">WALTER: </font>Bring him in.
<font color="#ff80ff">MARION: </font>Yes, yes.

715
01:02:08.972 --> 01:02:12.969
Tell him Robert is in the Holy Land,
sends his love and will return soon.

716
01:02:13.043 --> 01:02:16.237
Marion, our traveler will be thirsty.

717
01:02:16.246 --> 01:02:19.773
Travelers are always thirsty.
Is that not so?

718
01:02:19.849 --> 01:02:21.775
Your name, sir?

719
01:02:22.052 --> 01:02:24.979
Longstride. Robin Longstride.

720
01:02:26.823 --> 01:02:29.049
Do you mock me?

721
01:02:29.826 --> 01:02:31.450
Sir?

722
01:02:32.162 --> 01:02:33.824
Your son,

723
01:02:35.198 --> 01:02:37.995
he asked me to
bring you this.

724
01:02:45.608 --> 01:02:51.377
And how does Robert defend
himself if he has no sword?

725
01:02:51.581 --> 01:02:55.082
The prodigal son will
not return after all.

726
01:02:55.151 --> 01:02:57.145
<font color="#ff80ff">(EXHALES)</font>

727
01:02:57.153 --> 01:03:01.517
So, no tears, no forgiveness
from his father.

728
01:03:01.591 --> 01:03:04.754
<font color="#ff80ff">(CLEARING THROAT)</font>

729
01:03:05.562 --> 01:03:08.559
No amends to be made.

730
01:03:15.939 --> 01:03:18.602
Did you see him die?

731
01:03:20.043 --> 01:03:23.273
I was with him when he passed.

732
01:03:23.313 --> 01:03:27.382
His final words were for the love and
bond between a father and son.

733
01:03:27.417 --> 01:03:29.550
Forgive my rudeness.

734
01:03:30.420 --> 01:03:34.316
My grief has been
waiting for this day.

735
01:03:34.324 --> 01:03:38.216
So come, so that
I may see you.

736
01:03:52.775 --> 01:03:55.400
Robin Longstride.

737
01:03:56.045 --> 01:04:00.278
A common enough but
noble Saxon name.

738
01:04:01.684 --> 01:04:05.653
So, you will dine with us.

739
01:04:06.055 --> 01:04:08.946
But first, you must bathe, sir.

740
01:04:08.992 --> 01:04:10.784
You stink.

741
01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:22.302
I've laid out some of my husband's clothes.
I hope you don't find that too discomforting.

742
01:04:22.372 --> 01:04:23.600
<font color="#ff80ff">(MAIDS GIGGLING)</font>

743
01:04:23.673 --> 01:04:25.435
My Lady,

744
01:04:27.377 --> 01:04:30.938
I'll need some help
with the chain mail.

745
01:04:31.281 --> 01:04:33.043
Winifred.

746
01:04:34.150 --> 01:04:35.812
Winifred.

747
01:04:43.993 --> 01:04:49.320
The coif has a clasp at
the nape of the neck.

748
01:04:56.973 --> 01:05:02.966
If you take off the coif, you'll find
lacings in the back of the tabard.

749
01:05:28.338 --> 01:05:31.232
<font color="#ff80ff">(SIGHING)</font>

750
01:05:37.647 --> 01:05:39.080
Thank you.

751
01:05:39.148 --> 01:05:42.711
I'll have it washed.

752
01:05:58.334 --> 01:06:00.995
Marion, more wine.

753
01:06:04.874 --> 01:06:08.000
You've taken a long road
to bring this to me.

754
01:06:08.011 --> 01:06:11.412
I cannot decide whether
that makes you trustworthy.. .

755
01:06:11.481 --> 01:06:13.473
Or manipulative.

756
01:06:13.549 --> 01:06:19.148
Marion, I'm merely trying to gauge the
quality of the man we have as our guest.

757
01:06:19.188 --> 01:06:21.212
Is he handsome?

758
01:06:21.257 --> 01:06:22.849
Yes.

759
01:06:24.160 --> 01:06:28.119
In the way that yeomen sometimes
are when they are sober.

760
01:06:28.197 --> 01:06:31.698
Entertain us with a
tale of your life, sir.

761
01:06:31.734 --> 01:06:34.464
We don't get many
visitors anymore.

762
01:06:34.537 --> 01:06:37.967
Except tax collectors
and other beggars.

763
01:06:38.041 --> 01:06:41.340
I don't know where I'm from.
Only know where I've been.

764
01:06:41.411 --> 01:06:45.578
So, Marion, what color
are his eyes?

765
01:06:49.886 --> 01:06:52.213
I don't yet know.

766
01:06:52.288 --> 01:06:57.484
I have a proposal for you,
young man.

767
01:06:58.528 --> 01:07:01.754
You brought me this sword,
which has great meaning.

768
01:07:01.764 --> 01:07:04.395
If you give me your time,

769
01:07:04.667 --> 01:07:06.598
it is yours.

770
01:07:07.670 --> 01:07:11.833
I could stay for
a day or more.

771
01:07:13.543 --> 01:07:17.172
I have a question to ask you.
And what is your question?

772
01:07:17.246 --> 01:07:21.138
The words on the hilt of the sword,
what do they mean?

773
01:07:21.217 --> 01:07:27.220
Well, I think I have much to tell you
about history. About your history.

774
01:07:33.262 --> 01:07:34.627
That's very kind.

775
01:07:34.697 --> 01:07:37.860
Well, you haven't heard the
other half of my proposal yet.

776
01:07:37.934 --> 01:07:41.961
I want you to stay in Nottingham
and for the time being,

777
01:07:42.038 --> 01:07:46.234
become my returned son
and therefore Marion's spouse.

778
01:07:46.242 --> 01:07:47.470
That's enough!

779
01:07:47.543 --> 01:07:49.135
You've had too much to drink.
Listen. Listen.

780
01:07:49.212 --> 01:07:53.812
We both know that without a husband
you will lose this land when I die.

781
01:07:53.883 --> 01:07:56.078
Do you dispute that?

782
01:07:56.152 --> 01:07:58.882
No, so if I say this is my son,

783
01:07:58.955 --> 01:08:04.621
he will be seen as that.
And so, as your husband?

784
01:08:04.694 --> 01:08:06.623
It is a fair contract.

785
01:08:06.662 --> 01:08:11.423
It is not as if I expect
you to have children or.. .

786
01:08:11.501 --> 01:08:16.031
No, the sword for
your time, Longstride.

787
01:08:16.105 --> 01:08:18.267
Are you in agreement?

788
01:08:18.975 --> 01:08:22.108
Yes.
Marion, go tell the staff

789
01:08:22.111 --> 01:08:27.309
that my son has arrived and
our home is now whole again.

790
01:08:27.316 --> 01:08:30.880
Tell them to ring the church
bells in celebration.

791
01:08:30.920 --> 01:08:33.085
And more wine, please.

792
01:08:33.089 --> 01:08:36.950
<font color="#ff80ff">(PLAYING FOLK TUNE)</font>

793
01:08:43.199 --> 01:08:45.260
Hey! Hey!

794
01:08:49.972 --> 01:08:51.371
I rose up in the morning

795
01:08:51.441 --> 01:08:53.636
And I felt a dire need

796
01:08:53.709 --> 01:08:57.236
To dream away the dreary day
and down a cup of mead

797
01:08:57.313 --> 01:08:59.772
I felt the sting of honeybees

798
01:08:59.816 --> 01:09:01.647
Home brew.

799
01:09:02.485 --> 01:09:07.188
If I wasn't the village priest,
I'd try for the village drunkard.

800
01:09:07.190 --> 01:09:09.021
<font color="#ff80ff">(CROWD CHANTING)</font>

801
01:09:09.091 --> 01:09:10.749
Oh, great.

802
01:09:11.227 --> 01:09:13.661
<font color="#ff80ff">WILL:</font> A man could get
very affectionate here.

803
01:09:13.729 --> 01:09:19.890
I haven't seen so many women
for so few men outside a nunnery.

804
01:09:19.936 --> 01:09:25.096
The secret to success is
never go for the prettiest one.

805
01:09:25.208 --> 01:09:29.369
Start with the homely
one on the left.

806
01:09:31.380 --> 01:09:32.874
Right there.

807
01:09:32.949 --> 01:09:36.943
She's about my size.
I'm going to make her smile.

808
01:09:37.019 --> 01:09:39.919
I'm going to make you smile!

809
01:09:39.922 --> 01:09:41.080
Come over here!

810
01:09:41.157 --> 01:09:44.058
So, why do they
call you Little John?

811
01:09:44.126 --> 01:09:46.457
What are you trying to get at?

812
01:09:46.496 --> 01:09:47.690
I'm proportionate.

813
01:09:47.763 --> 01:09:50.823
So roll another barrel to the bar

814
01:09:50.900 --> 01:09:55.631
And pour another cup or two
so l can soak my heart

815
01:10:27.270 --> 01:10:30.928
<font color="#ff80ff">(PIGEONS COOING)</font>

816
01:10:43.686 --> 01:10:46.014
Stop it.

817
01:10:48.324 --> 01:10:51.389
What did I tell you?

818
01:10:59.569 --> 01:11:02.994
It seems we are to
share my chamber.

819
01:11:03.072 --> 01:11:06.739
A ruse to convince
the servants.

820
01:11:06.776 --> 01:11:10.302
Well, if the aim is deception,

821
01:11:10.379 --> 01:11:16.449
should you not be addressing me
as ''My husband'' or ''My dear''?

822
01:11:16.485 --> 01:11:19.853
Don't be ridiculous.

823
01:11:23.059 --> 01:11:26.686
Well, are you coming or not?

824
01:11:29.098 --> 01:11:31.626
Ask me nicely.

825
01:11:38.307 --> 01:11:42.073
Please, dear husband,
will you share my chamber?

826
01:12:18.881 --> 01:12:20.339
Here.

827
01:12:23.953 --> 01:12:25.716
I sleep with a dagger.

828
01:12:25.788 --> 01:12:29.724
If you so much as move to touch me,
I will sever your manhood.

829
01:12:29.792 --> 01:12:31.054
You understand?

830
01:12:31.394 --> 01:12:32.452
Thanks for the warning.

831
01:12:39.368 --> 01:12:40.630
Hello, dogs.

832
01:13:21.977 --> 01:13:23.904
<font color="#ff80ff">(WHISTLING)</font>

833
01:13:25.014 --> 01:13:26.879
<font color="#ff80ff">(ANSWERING WHISTLE)</font>

834
01:14:06.422 --> 01:14:08.319
<font color="#ff80ff">(SOLDIERS EXCLAIMING)</font>

835
01:14:30.112 --> 01:14:32.478
<font color="#ff80ff">(MARSHAL READING)</font>

836
01:14:36.385 --> 01:14:38.113
Godfrey.

837
01:14:48.197 --> 01:14:50.226
Where are your men?

838
01:14:50.933 --> 01:14:52.861
They're dead, My Lord.

839
01:14:53.302 --> 01:14:54.428
And Loxley?

840
01:14:54.703 --> 01:14:55.863
Alive.

841
01:14:59.542 --> 01:15:00.941
Then fate has left him to me.

842
01:15:13.255 --> 01:15:17.282
I hear a man's steps.
Good morning, my son.

843
01:15:18.093 --> 01:15:20.060
Morning, Walter.

844
01:15:20.729 --> 01:15:22.121
Father.

845
01:15:22.198 --> 01:15:23.926
Father.

846
01:15:24.166 --> 01:15:26.532
So what is it that you
know of my history?

847
01:15:26.602 --> 01:15:27.899
Patience.

848
01:15:28.337 --> 01:15:32.000
You must show yourself today.
Wear your sword.

849
01:15:33.542 --> 01:15:35.231
Marion.

850
01:15:35.544 --> 01:15:36.772
I'm here, Walter.

851
01:15:36.846 --> 01:15:40.839
Reacquaint your husband
with his village and his people.

852
01:15:42.718 --> 01:15:45.016
I'll see to the horses.

853
01:15:45.287 --> 01:15:46.811
I feel invigorated.

854
01:15:46.989 --> 01:15:50.390
I woke this morning with
a tumescent glow.

855
01:15:51.060 --> 01:15:52.254
Eighty-four.

856
01:15:53.062 --> 01:15:54.427
A miracle.

857
01:15:56.031 --> 01:15:59.626
I've always wondered at the
private conversations of men.

858
01:16:00.436 --> 01:16:01.733
Husband.

859
01:16:22.091 --> 01:16:24.222
This is rich country.

860
01:16:24.526 --> 01:16:26.494
Where's your cattle
and your sheep?

861
01:16:26.562 --> 01:16:30.521
Sold, eaten, stolen, traded.
We've had seven lean years.

862
01:16:31.066 --> 01:16:33.432
Our meat now is rabbit

863
01:16:33.502 --> 01:16:36.198
or wild pig on a lucky day.

864
01:16:36.272 --> 01:16:37.569
And deer?

865
01:16:37.907 --> 01:16:41.809
If you're willing to risk your neck
to the King's executioner.

866
01:16:42.177 --> 01:16:44.839
Every deer in the land
belongs to His Majesty.

867
01:16:44.914 --> 01:16:47.678
These things are God's gifts first
before the King's possessions.

868
01:16:48.317 --> 01:16:52.117
If it's illegal for a man
to fend for himself

869
01:16:52.187 --> 01:16:54.087
how then can he be a
man in his own right?

870
01:16:54.156 --> 01:16:56.021
Welcome home, sir.

871
01:16:56.091 --> 01:16:59.288
<font color="#ff80ff">JOSEPH:</font> Sir Robert.
Good morning, Joseph. Emma.

872
01:17:00.863 --> 01:17:04.822
Sir Walter is our Lord, and you are
Robert returned and you should act so.

873
01:17:07.536 --> 01:17:09.834
Sir Robert. You remember me?

874
01:17:09.905 --> 01:17:12.430
Tom Chamberlain. Pig farmer.

875
01:17:12.775 --> 01:17:14.299
You don't look a day older, Tom.

876
01:17:15.311 --> 01:17:17.176
Sir Robert.

877
01:17:17.313 --> 01:17:19.611
When will our young
lads come back to us?

878
01:17:20.182 --> 01:17:23.117
Will you find my Jamie,
tell him to come home?

879
01:17:25.888 --> 01:17:29.722
With no work and little food,
the village boys have gone.

880
01:17:29.792 --> 01:17:32.192
To be soldiers?
Poachers.

881
01:17:37.566 --> 01:17:38.999
Look at that, mate.

882
01:17:42.037 --> 01:17:43.732
Still here then?

883
01:17:45.708 --> 01:17:49.804
For the time being, refer to me
as Sir Robert. I'll explain later.

884
01:17:50.212 --> 01:17:54.046
My men-at-arms.
This is about as courtly as they get.

885
01:17:54.483 --> 01:17:57.884
Allan A'Dayle, Will Scarlet
and Little John.

886
01:17:57.953 --> 01:17:59.079
Lady Marion.

887
01:18:05.894 --> 01:18:08.920
I trust you had an historic evening.

888
01:18:09.465 --> 01:18:10.625
For sure.

889
01:18:15.204 --> 01:18:18.469
Lady Marion Loxley.
My wife.

890
01:18:19.241 --> 01:18:20.708
Well played.

891
01:18:21.243 --> 01:18:24.576
A bit rash but well
played nonetheless.

892
01:18:24.646 --> 01:18:26.238
Right you are, Robin.

893
01:18:26.448 --> 01:18:27.745
Sir Robert.

894
01:18:27.816 --> 01:18:29.408
Sir Robert.
Sir.. .

895
01:18:30.019 --> 01:18:31.816
Sir. Sir.

896
01:18:31.887 --> 01:18:33.548
Sir Bob.
Sir Robert.

897
01:18:40.863 --> 01:18:42.125
Friar.

898
01:18:43.699 --> 01:18:48.363
Marion. Good news travels
from Peper Harow this morning.

899
01:18:49.171 --> 01:18:51.662
Sir Robert, nice to see you again.

900
01:18:51.740 --> 01:18:55.437
You should've made yourself known
when we met in the field. Welcome home.

901
01:18:56.145 --> 01:18:58.807
Yes, I should've.
Forgive me, Friar.

902
01:19:00.049 --> 01:19:01.516
What happens here?

903
01:19:01.583 --> 01:19:04.051
We're moving the Church's grain to York.

904
01:19:04.119 --> 01:19:05.882
Politics out of London, I hear.

905
01:19:05.954 --> 01:19:08.923
This is our grain.
It belongs in this soil.

906
01:19:08.991 --> 01:19:12.017
Lady Marion, I but follow
the orders of my superiors

907
01:19:12.094 --> 01:19:14.494
and abide by their
saying and rule.

908
01:19:19.535 --> 01:19:22.026
Does His Holiness know
about your wealth of honey?

909
01:19:23.972 --> 01:19:28.204
There are wolves in York, Sir Robert.
Voracious wolves.

910
01:19:29.611 --> 01:19:31.306
The bees are my family.

911
01:19:31.747 --> 01:19:33.908
I'm a procreator by design.

912
01:19:34.616 --> 01:19:37.380
I'm not a churchy friar.
Never was.

913
01:19:38.220 --> 01:19:39.983
My bees give life.

914
01:19:40.689 --> 01:19:42.452
They are my life, Sir Robert.

915
01:19:42.524 --> 01:19:44.424
Should not the Bishop be told

916
01:19:44.560 --> 01:19:47.688
so the clergy can spread
Nottingham honey on Nottingham bread?

917
01:19:50.999 --> 01:19:53.900
What if the grain were
not to reach York?

918
01:19:55.337 --> 01:19:58.704
Then the bees need
not be spoken of.

919
01:20:07.816 --> 01:20:11.047
I was an old maid
when Robert courted me.

920
01:20:11.120 --> 01:20:15.489
I was a daughter of a respectable widow
with a thimbleful of noble blood.

921
01:20:15.924 --> 01:20:19.655
We were wed and
then a week later

922
01:20:20.062 --> 01:20:23.828
he left to join ship for
France and the Holy Lands.

923
01:20:23.899 --> 01:20:26.925
And that was my
married life to a man

924
01:20:28.937 --> 01:20:30.632
I hardly knew.

925
01:20:33.675 --> 01:20:36.109
A good knight. Short, but sweet.

926
01:20:37.179 --> 01:20:40.307
I mean, he was a good knight.

927
01:20:40.883 --> 01:20:42.874
A good knight-at-arms, a soldier.

928
01:20:42.951 --> 01:20:45.283
Oh yes, my knight-in-arms,
even so.

929
01:20:45.354 --> 01:20:47.117
And I in his.

930
01:21:13.382 --> 01:21:15.377
<font color="#ff80ff">(BLEATING)</font>

931
01:21:17.986 --> 01:21:20.420
Stop! You'll break its neck.

932
01:21:33.502 --> 01:21:34.730
Marion.

933
01:21:43.812 --> 01:21:44.938
Easy.

934
01:21:48.684 --> 01:21:49.878
I'm all right.

935
01:21:52.254 --> 01:21:54.051
I can't move me legs.

936
01:21:55.090 --> 01:21:56.455
I can't move me legs.

937
01:21:58.860 --> 01:22:00.088
Thank you.

938
01:22:03.332 --> 01:22:04.663
My Lord?

939
01:22:17.679 --> 01:22:19.476
Is it my turn now?

940
01:22:28.690 --> 01:22:29.850
Thank you.

941
01:22:31.827 --> 01:22:34.352
Nicely done, sir.

942
01:22:34.429 --> 01:22:39.264
And to see Lady Marion Loxley's legs,
beyond my wildest hopes this morning.

943
01:22:41.470 --> 01:22:45.429
I don't believe you
know my husband,

944
01:22:45.907 --> 01:22:46.965
Sir Robert.

945
01:22:47.042 --> 01:22:50.637
Allow me to introduce
the Sheriff of Nottingham.

946
01:22:50.712 --> 01:22:52.441
Welcome home, Sir Robert.

947
01:22:52.514 --> 01:22:56.382
You make your mark quickly by
rescuing the King's ram from drowning.

948
01:22:56.885 --> 01:22:57.943
What's this?

949
01:22:58.020 --> 01:23:02.252
What's mine in coin l have the right
to take in goods or livestock.

950
01:23:03.458 --> 01:23:05.255
If it's God's will.

951
01:23:08.864 --> 01:23:11.355
Here's a ram's worth of
tax for the Exchequer.

952
01:23:11.433 --> 01:23:15.893
Your insolence to Lady Marion,
I'll consider a debt between us.

953
01:23:41.897 --> 01:23:44.161
Mead and grain alcohol?

954
01:23:44.232 --> 01:23:46.530
I thought as much.

955
01:23:49.638 --> 01:23:51.833
There's something
that we need to do.

956
01:23:51.907 --> 01:23:53.670
At your service.

957
01:24:06.188 --> 01:24:07.416
All right, lads.

958
01:24:07.489 --> 01:24:11.789
Should've left while you had the chance.
Something's afoot. Off we go.

959
01:24:12.994 --> 01:24:15.093
<font color="#ff80ff">(OWL HOOTlNG)</font>

960
01:24:27.409 --> 01:24:29.536
<font color="#ff80ff">DEACON: </font>Stop. Stop the horses.

961
01:24:31.646 --> 01:24:35.309
You there! Move aside!
We're on Church business!

962
01:24:36.318 --> 01:24:38.252
None shall pass

963
01:24:38.320 --> 01:24:40.948
unless they can answer the riddle.

964
01:24:41.356 --> 01:24:43.187
Moon-mad!

965
01:24:43.258 --> 01:24:46.887
And what is the riddle,
you insolent wretch?

966
01:24:47.696 --> 01:24:52.224
What has 18 legs and
isn't going anywhere?

967
01:24:55.270 --> 01:24:57.602
Your next move will
be your last.

968
01:24:58.840 --> 01:25:00.102
Evening, friend.

969
01:25:02.144 --> 01:25:04.578
I demand to know who you are.

970
01:25:05.046 --> 01:25:06.240
We are men of the hood.

971
01:25:06.314 --> 01:25:08.281
<font color="#ff80ff">(WHISTLlNG)</font>

972
01:25:08.850 --> 01:25:10.408
Merry now, at your expense.

973
01:25:11.853 --> 01:25:13.184
''The Lord taketh.. .' '

974
01:25:13.255 --> 01:25:14.654
And we shall giveth back.

975
01:25:14.723 --> 01:25:17.248
My advice is to plant it
now, by moonlight.

976
01:25:17.592 --> 01:25:18.650
Why is that, good friar?

977
01:25:18.727 --> 01:25:21.821
When it sprouts, I can claim
it as a miracle from God.

978
01:25:21.897 --> 01:25:24.923
The Church in York
would never deny a miracle.

979
01:25:29.104 --> 01:25:31.834
How much further?
About 11 miles.

980
01:26:06.875 --> 01:26:09.233
<font color="#ff80ff">(THUNDER RUMBLING)</font>

981
01:26:22.224 --> 01:26:24.249
I thought you had left.

982
01:26:25.293 --> 01:26:27.454
The fields have been planted.

983
01:26:28.263 --> 01:26:30.288
I didn't want to wake you.

984
01:26:30.866 --> 01:26:32.527
How did you find the seed?

985
01:26:33.235 --> 01:26:35.601
If you have to ask,
it's not a gift.

986
01:26:37.706 --> 01:26:39.173
Thank you.

987
01:27:17.712 --> 01:27:20.043
<font color="#ff80ff">(GRUNTlNG)</font>

988
01:27:20.115 --> 01:27:22.173
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMlNG)</font>

989
01:27:26.221 --> 01:27:28.086
Arms to ready!

990
01:27:28.156 --> 01:27:29.646
Prepare!

991
01:27:30.458 --> 01:27:32.949
This King John is no king of mine!

992
01:27:34.529 --> 01:27:37.362
You! Are you Baldwin?
Open these gates!

993
01:27:37.432 --> 01:27:39.195
In whose name do
you come against us?

994
01:27:39.267 --> 01:27:41.292
In the name of King John.

995
01:27:41.703 --> 01:27:44.263
Pay or burn.

996
01:27:44.339 --> 01:27:47.831
We have paid in money and
men for King Richard's wars!

997
01:27:48.043 --> 01:27:50.170
And we have no more to give!

998
01:27:50.312 --> 01:27:52.143
Burn it.
Archers!

999
01:28:12.200 --> 01:28:13.928
Come on.

1000
01:28:19.574 --> 01:28:21.735
<font color="#ff80ff">(SOLDIERS SHOUTING)</font>

1001
01:28:25.447 --> 01:28:27.544
My Lord, this way!

1002
01:28:31.553 --> 01:28:33.578
In the name of John,

1003
01:28:33.655 --> 01:28:36.818
by the Grace of God, King of England,

1004
01:28:36.891 --> 01:28:42.420
let it be known to all who abide
here that a tax is warranted!

1005
01:28:48.136 --> 01:28:51.401
Those persons refusing
to abide by the law

1006
01:28:51.473 --> 01:28:54.931
will hereby be subject
to severe punishment.

1007
01:28:59.814 --> 01:29:02.806
By order of His Majesty, King John.

1008
01:29:03.284 --> 01:29:05.616
<font color="#ff80ff">(BELL TOLLlNG)</font>

1009
01:29:14.329 --> 01:29:15.660
Father Tancred!

1010
01:29:20.669 --> 01:29:22.429
<font color="#ff80ff">(GROANlNG)</font>

1011
01:29:33.314 --> 01:29:34.645
Your Majesty.

1012
01:29:38.019 --> 01:29:39.577
Your Majesty.

1013
01:29:42.524 --> 01:29:45.254
I have lost the confidence
of King John,

1014
01:29:45.694 --> 01:29:47.491
but he may still listen to you.

1015
01:29:47.562 --> 01:29:50.030
Allow me to know better, William.

1016
01:29:50.265 --> 01:29:52.597
You are much wiser
than your owl.

1017
01:29:52.667 --> 01:29:55.795
I dare say. I've lived longer.

1018
01:29:57.138 --> 01:29:58.867
Edward, take him.

1019
01:29:58.940 --> 01:30:00.698
<font color="#ff80ff">EDWARD:</font> Your Majesty.

1020
01:30:03.511 --> 01:30:06.844
John is no Richard,
alas, Your Majesty.

1021
01:30:08.983 --> 01:30:13.647
But I serve the throne,
and the throne will endure.

1022
01:30:16.357 --> 01:30:19.326
Speak plainly, Marshal.
What's troubling you?

1023
01:30:20.061 --> 01:30:22.052
The crown is in peril.

1024
01:30:23.264 --> 01:30:26.529
Godfrey has been plotting
with Philip of France.

1025
01:30:27.569 --> 01:30:29.594
French troops have already
landed on our shores,

1026
01:30:29.671 --> 01:30:32.401
and they are murdering Englishmen
in the name of King John.

1027
01:30:33.274 --> 01:30:37.267
The northern barons will make
civil war against the throne.

1028
01:30:37.545 --> 01:30:40.878
Leaving our coast defenseless
against the invasion

1029
01:30:41.583 --> 01:30:43.608
which is certainly coming.

1030
01:30:46.054 --> 01:30:51.048
So it's left to John's mother to scold him
like a child and point him to his duty.

1031
01:30:56.865 --> 01:31:01.427
My son has an enemy in his court
closer to him than any friend.

1032
01:31:01.536 --> 01:31:05.097
An English traitor.
A paid agent of France.

1033
01:31:06.274 --> 01:31:09.300
Why are you telling me
when you must tell the King?

1034
01:31:09.377 --> 01:31:10.810
<font color="#ff80ff">ELEANOR:</font> Isabella!

1035
01:31:11.880 --> 01:31:14.110
It is you who must do that.

1036
01:31:14.682 --> 01:31:18.812
Tell King John that you've had word
from France, from Philip himself, if you like.

1037
01:31:18.887 --> 01:31:22.050
Why not tell him the truth?
That William Marshal.. .

1038
01:31:22.123 --> 01:31:26.822
A mother he mistrusts bearing
the word of a man in dishonor?

1039
01:31:26.895 --> 01:31:28.021
No.

1040
01:31:28.930 --> 01:31:33.299
If you wish to be queen,
you must save John.

1041
01:31:34.836 --> 01:31:36.269
And England.

1042
01:31:37.739 --> 01:31:39.533
No!

1043
01:31:39.808 --> 01:31:41.605
No! No!

1044
01:31:41.976 --> 01:31:44.136
<font color="#ff80ff">(ISABELLA GASPING)</font>

1045
01:31:44.546 --> 01:31:47.481
Godfrey! The bloody Judas!

1046
01:31:48.249 --> 01:31:50.843
By the bowels of Christ,
it's a lie.

1047
01:31:50.919 --> 01:31:52.750
You lie!

1048
01:32:11.472 --> 01:32:13.633
I'm sorry, my love.

1049
01:32:29.624 --> 01:32:31.815
Sheriff. Up there.

1050
01:32:35.530 --> 01:32:38.727
Man won't give his name.
Demands audience with the sheriff.

1051
01:32:39.267 --> 01:32:41.132
Demands?

1052
01:32:43.538 --> 01:32:45.631
Go away. My Lord.

1053
01:33:07.829 --> 01:33:10.457
<font color="#ff80ff">BELVEDERE:</font> Tax collections proceed apace.

1054
01:33:11.432 --> 01:33:13.229
Nottingham's turn is coming.

1055
01:33:13.568 --> 01:33:15.536
Good. Good.

1056
01:33:15.737 --> 01:33:19.503
Tell Sir Godfrey that the
Sheriff of Nottingham is his man.

1057
01:33:19.574 --> 01:33:22.304
May he put his stamp
on my authority.

1058
01:33:22.377 --> 01:33:27.144
I see trouble coming
from Loxley of Peper Harow.

1059
01:33:27.749 --> 01:33:29.580
A blind old man gives you trouble?

1060
01:33:29.651 --> 01:33:31.812
Aye and his son will give more.

1061
01:33:31.986 --> 01:33:36.218
The crusader, Robert Loxley,
has returned this past week.

1062
01:33:52.907 --> 01:33:55.466
<font color="#ff80ff">(CREAKING)</font>

1063
01:34:13.795 --> 01:34:14.989
Marion.

1064
01:34:22.236 --> 01:34:24.661
<font color="#ff80ff">(BOAR SQUEALING)</font>

1065
01:34:32.613 --> 01:34:34.575
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMING)</font>

1066
01:34:56.804 --> 01:34:58.533
<font color="#ff80ff">(WHOOPING)</font>

1067
01:35:18.726 --> 01:35:20.819
Go on! Go on.

1068
01:35:26.300 --> 01:35:27.858
Has he spoken yet?

1069
01:35:28.102 --> 01:35:29.228
He was spying, Loop.

1070
01:35:29.704 --> 01:35:31.103
Spying?

1071
01:35:32.640 --> 01:35:35.108
Robert, I'm ashamed of you.

1072
01:35:35.543 --> 01:35:36.874
Hello, Marion.

1073
01:35:37.311 --> 01:35:39.344
I've come to save you.

1074
01:35:40.014 --> 01:35:41.740
<font color="#ff80ff">LOOP:</font> Know him?

1075
01:35:41.816 --> 01:35:46.446
Boys, this is Sir Robert Loxley, my husband.

1076
01:35:46.888 --> 01:35:50.016
Sir Robert, the runaways of Sherwood.

1077
01:35:50.992 --> 01:35:52.323
Untie him.

1078
01:35:52.393 --> 01:35:56.193
No, I don't think spies
should be let off so easily.

1079
01:35:56.798 --> 01:35:58.163
That was unkind.

1080
01:35:58.232 --> 01:36:00.829
You were a crusader?
Yes.

1081
01:36:01.302 --> 01:36:04.271
Did you hear that, boys?
You bested a crusader.

1082
01:36:05.673 --> 01:36:07.937
My men are good fighters.
I don't know about that.

1083
01:36:08.009 --> 01:36:10.443
I think the weight of numbers
might have been in their favor.

1084
01:36:10.511 --> 01:36:13.241
But they do move silently
like the creatures of the forest.

1085
01:36:13.314 --> 01:36:15.441
But that's only a skill
if you stay as a man.

1086
01:36:15.516 --> 01:36:17.609
You don't become the
creatures you hunt.

1087
01:36:17.685 --> 01:36:20.017
We're soldiers.
No, you're not.

1088
01:36:20.188 --> 01:36:23.214
Soldiers fight for a cause.
What's yours?

1089
01:36:25.460 --> 01:36:28.429
You don't have one.
That makes you poachers.

1090
01:36:28.496 --> 01:36:29.690
<font color="#ff80ff">(CHILDREN MUTTERING ANGRILY)</font>

1091
01:36:29.764 --> 01:36:33.131
Common thieves with a lot to learn.

1092
01:36:33.201 --> 01:36:34.293
Like what?

1093
01:36:34.368 --> 01:36:36.632
I could teach you
how to tie knots.

1094
01:36:36.704 --> 01:36:39.605
I could teach you which wood to
get to make your bows stronger.

1095
01:36:39.674 --> 01:36:43.906
I could teach you how to make arrows
that fly more than 20 feet.

1096
01:36:44.345 --> 01:36:47.678
And I can help Marion to teach
you how to stay clean

1097
01:36:47.815 --> 01:36:49.783
so you won't get sick.

1098
01:36:50.251 --> 01:36:54.881
I don't know who you're fighting, son,
but it's not me. l'm not your enemy.

1099
01:36:55.790 --> 01:36:58.884
If you want to chat,
you know where to find me.

1100
01:37:13.141 --> 01:37:14.267
Wife?

1101
01:37:21.916 --> 01:37:23.406
Marshal.

1102
01:37:23.985 --> 01:37:26.351
Stand aside! Make way
for the King!

1103
01:37:26.420 --> 01:37:27.944
Your Majesty.

1104
01:37:29.757 --> 01:37:32.692
What the devil are
you doing here?

1105
01:37:32.760 --> 01:37:33.852
Sire?

1106
01:37:33.928 --> 01:37:37.195
Will you keep that animal still?
What's it got, palsy?

1107
01:37:39.300 --> 01:37:41.393
Do you think I haven't noticed
how you've deserted me?

1108
01:37:41.469 --> 01:37:43.903
If Your Majesty recalls,
our last conversation.. .

1109
01:37:43.971 --> 01:37:45.370
At our last conversation,

1110
01:37:45.439 --> 01:37:48.738
Philip of France wasn't coming our
way with an invasion fleet.

1111
01:37:49.377 --> 01:37:51.340
Was he, Marshal?

1112
01:37:54.882 --> 01:37:56.947
My friend Godfrey

1113
01:37:57.652 --> 01:38:00.485
is not the friend I
thought he was.

1114
01:38:01.289 --> 01:38:04.019
He's stirred up the northern
barons against me.

1115
01:38:04.592 --> 01:38:06.924
They come south with an army.

1116
01:38:08.563 --> 01:38:10.997
Marshal, how dare they?
How dare they?

1117
01:38:11.065 --> 01:38:13.898
Sire, forgotten men are
dangerous men.

1118
01:38:16.103 --> 01:38:18.663
The barons need to be told

1119
01:38:19.240 --> 01:38:22.676
that when the French come,
we are all Englishmen.

1120
01:38:23.744 --> 01:38:26.008
Fitzrobert. Baldwin.

1121
01:38:27.081 --> 01:38:30.380
We'll make an army of the
north and march on London.

1122
01:38:30.985 --> 01:38:33.112
The barons need leadership.

1123
01:38:33.421 --> 01:38:37.323
Wiser kings know they must
let men look them in the eye,

1124
01:38:38.192 --> 01:38:40.092
hear their voice.

1125
01:38:40.761 --> 01:38:44.322
Together, let us ride
north to meet them.

1126
01:38:47.134 --> 01:38:49.728
They march against their
king, Marshal.

1127
01:38:52.073 --> 01:38:53.563
Their king.

1128
01:38:55.042 --> 01:38:59.035
We will meet them with the pikes
of our militia in their gizzards.

1129
01:38:59.714 --> 01:39:01.978
You have lost your touch, Marshal.

1130
01:39:04.218 --> 01:39:06.618
Perhaps we'll look to the
barons without you.

1131
01:39:17.798 --> 01:39:20.961
Saddle up with a spare horse.
l leave immediately.

1132
01:39:21.035 --> 01:39:22.559
I want to know where
to find Godfrey.

1133
01:39:22.637 --> 01:39:23.968
My Lord.

1134
01:39:39.120 --> 01:39:41.714
I found him, My Lord.
Where?

1135
01:39:41.789 --> 01:39:46.055
Nottingham. In plain sight, living
as Walter Loxley's son.

1136
01:39:51.966 --> 01:39:53.991
Then we go to Nottingham.

1137
01:39:54.502 --> 01:39:57.528
Take no prisoners.
Leave no stone un-scorched.

1138
01:40:00.975 --> 01:40:02.806
Take two men, four horses.

1139
01:40:02.877 --> 01:40:07.109
Ride hard for the coast, then on to Paris
and give a message to the King.

1140
01:40:24.865 --> 01:40:27.163
I'll make the place famous.

1141
01:40:30.671 --> 01:40:32.161
Come, Allan!

1142
01:40:32.239 --> 01:40:35.367
I'll get them drinking.
You get them dancing!

1143
01:40:35.476 --> 01:40:36.534
All right.

1144
01:40:38.879 --> 01:40:41.470
<font color="#ff80ff">(PLAYING FOLK TUNE)</font>

1145
01:41:03.838 --> 01:41:05.066
<font color="#ff80ff">(SIGHING)</font>

1146
01:41:07.541 --> 01:41:12.638
Music, laughter, the crackle
of a bonfire and a roasting pig.

1147
01:41:12.947 --> 01:41:16.474
Life has returned.
You have returned it, Robin.

1148
01:41:34.435 --> 01:41:37.226
<font color="#ff80ff">(BAND PLAYING BALLAD)</font>

1149
01:43:12.466 --> 01:43:15.398
<font color="#ff80ff">(SPEAKING LATIN)</font>

1150
01:43:16.704 --> 01:43:18.672
How did you know it was me?

1151
01:43:18.739 --> 01:43:22.334
Who else would sit
by me uninvited

1152
01:43:23.143 --> 01:43:25.737
like a friend from the old days?

1153
01:43:26.313 --> 01:43:27.974
How are you, William?

1154
01:43:28.782 --> 01:43:31.615
I'm well and troubled.

1155
01:43:31.685 --> 01:43:34.176
And what brings you?

1156
01:43:34.455 --> 01:43:37.322
I'm riding on to Barnsdale tonight.

1157
01:43:37.491 --> 01:43:41.723
I've heard something of the barons' anger
against the crown's tax collector.. .

1158
01:43:41.795 --> 01:43:44.195
The anger has turned into action.

1159
01:43:44.365 --> 01:43:46.424
They assemble to
march against the King.

1160
01:43:46.767 --> 01:43:49.133
You think you can persuade
the barons to turn back?

1161
01:43:49.203 --> 01:43:50.295
Turn back, no.

1162
01:43:51.505 --> 01:43:55.441
To join King John against
a French invasion.

1163
01:43:56.644 --> 01:43:58.737
A what?
Help me, Walter.

1164
01:43:59.113 --> 01:44:01.047
I cannot go with you.

1165
01:44:02.016 --> 01:44:03.745
I cannot speak for this king.

1166
01:44:03.817 --> 01:44:05.409
He is the only king we have.

1167
01:44:05.486 --> 01:44:06.885
But not the only hope.

1168
01:44:07.988 --> 01:44:09.148
Explain.

1169
01:44:10.724 --> 01:44:12.954
Marion.
I'm here, Walter.

1170
01:44:13.294 --> 01:44:15.558
This is my old friend,
William Marshal.

1171
01:44:15.629 --> 01:44:18.120
Lady Marion Loxley,
my son's wife.

1172
01:44:18.198 --> 01:44:21.065
Lady, I was glad to see Sir Robert
when he disembarked in London.

1173
01:44:21.135 --> 01:44:23.626
I think you know better, Marshal.

1174
01:44:23.704 --> 01:44:28.471
Sir William, I know, would like
to meet Robin Longstride again.

1175
01:44:39.653 --> 01:44:41.086
We've met before.

1176
01:44:41.155 --> 01:44:43.555
Yes, Sir, I know.
In London.

1177
01:44:45.392 --> 01:44:47.792
No, when you were a child.

1178
01:44:49.663 --> 01:44:51.290
Hobby-horse age.

1179
01:44:52.066 --> 01:44:55.968
Sir Walter and I returned from
the Holy Land to fetch you home.

1180
01:44:56.503 --> 01:44:57.765
But you'd gone.

1181
01:44:57.838 --> 01:45:00.966
We had lost Thomas Longstride's son.

1182
01:45:03.510 --> 01:45:07.071
It was a wound that never healed.

1183
01:45:14.021 --> 01:45:17.013
You need to know what I know.

1184
01:45:18.025 --> 01:45:20.960
Your father was a stonemason.

1185
01:45:22.162 --> 01:45:24.153
Is that pleasing to you?

1186
01:45:26.400 --> 01:45:28.527
Yes. It is.

1187
01:45:29.269 --> 01:45:32.432
But he was more than that.
He was a visionary.

1188
01:45:33.207 --> 01:45:34.868
What did he see?

1189
01:45:35.442 --> 01:45:38.104
That kings have a need
of their subjects

1190
01:45:38.178 --> 01:45:42.046
no less than their subjects
have need of kings.

1191
01:45:42.116 --> 01:45:43.777
A dangerous idea.

1192
01:45:44.351 --> 01:45:47.616
Your father was a philosopher.
He had a way of speaking

1193
01:45:47.688 --> 01:45:50.816
that took you by the ears
and by the heart.

1194
01:45:51.258 --> 01:45:54.125
None of these things
can be written down, Robin.

1195
01:45:54.194 --> 01:45:56.958
You must commit them
to your very soul.

1196
01:45:57.698 --> 01:45:59.563
This is the science of memory.

1197
01:46:00.034 --> 01:46:05.438
''Rise and rise again
until lambs become lions.' '

1198
01:46:07.875 --> 01:46:13.108
Finally, hundreds listened,
thousands, who took up his call

1199
01:46:13.347 --> 01:46:16.612
for the rights of all ranks
from baron to serf.

1200
01:46:19.586 --> 01:46:21.247
''Rise and rise again

1201
01:46:23.490 --> 01:46:25.720
''until lambs become lions.' '

1202
01:46:30.831 --> 01:46:32.662
What happened to him?

1203
01:46:33.500 --> 01:46:35.195
Close your eyes.

1204
01:46:41.408 --> 01:46:45.640
... foundation is set on
the rights of liberty for all people!

1205
01:46:50.284 --> 01:46:53.685
Longstride, give up the charter
and their names!

1206
01:46:53.921 --> 01:46:55.445
You were there.

1207
01:46:55.756 --> 01:46:57.018
You saw it.

1208
01:47:00.260 --> 01:47:01.693
l will not.

1209
01:47:13.040 --> 01:47:14.902
<font color="#ff80ff">(SHOUTING)</font>

1210
01:47:25.886 --> 01:47:27.251
Not dead.

1211
01:47:28.722 --> 01:47:30.019
Not now.

1212
01:47:32.893 --> 01:47:34.121
Not now.

1213
01:47:38.499 --> 01:47:42.196
Here is my copy
of the main contract.

1214
01:47:42.603 --> 01:47:46.130
This charter of rights
was written by your father.

1215
01:47:46.206 --> 01:47:50.233
And here are.. . There are the names
of all the barons that signed the charter.

1216
01:47:50.310 --> 01:47:53.711
Fitzrobert, Baldwin,
Marshal and myself.

1217
01:47:54.248 --> 01:47:57.547
What he wanted was
a charter for every man.. .

1218
01:47:57.618 --> 01:48:00.178
Wait there.
.. .to have the same rights.

1219
01:48:00.254 --> 01:48:03.382
Sir Walter? A messenger for you.

1220
01:48:03.457 --> 01:48:05.481
<font color="#ff80ff">WALTER: </font>Bring him in.

1221
01:48:05.692 --> 01:48:07.421
Step forward, sir.

1222
01:48:08.495 --> 01:48:10.986
My Lord.
<font color="#ff80ff">WALTER:</font> I'm listening.

1223
01:48:11.131 --> 01:48:13.395
Peterborough's been
burned by the King's men.

1224
01:48:13.934 --> 01:48:16.767
Fitzrobert gathers an army
to slay King John in London.

1225
01:48:16.837 --> 01:48:20.329
Marshal requests your presence
at counsel in Barnsdale.

1226
01:48:22.042 --> 01:48:24.340
Wait outside, will you?

1227
01:48:25.646 --> 01:48:28.080
Cometh the hour,
cometh the man.

1228
01:48:29.249 --> 01:48:31.945
The time for pretense is over.

1229
01:48:33.253 --> 01:48:35.949
Now, hold me like a son.

1230
01:48:43.397 --> 01:48:44.421
Go.

1231
01:48:45.999 --> 01:48:48.934
Maggie. Where's my lady?

1232
01:48:49.036 --> 01:48:50.503
I could not find her, sir.

1233
01:49:16.563 --> 01:49:21.398
Whether we fight for our lives,
our family and our honor,

1234
01:49:21.468 --> 01:49:23.231
we must fight till the death.

1235
01:49:24.238 --> 01:49:27.071
You've spent too long
in the palace, William.

1236
01:49:27.174 --> 01:49:30.507
Spending time in the palace
gives me perspective.

1237
01:49:31.645 --> 01:49:33.306
As we speak,

1238
01:49:34.381 --> 01:49:37.145
King Philip sails
for our coast.

1239
01:49:38.185 --> 01:49:42.679
Godfrey and his
marauders are French!

1240
01:49:44.358 --> 01:49:47.259
Every minute that we
waste in disunity

1241
01:49:47.327 --> 01:49:50.558
brings closer the destruction of our country!

1242
01:49:51.031 --> 01:49:52.896
<font color="#ff80ff">FITZROBERT:</font> We have been bled

1243
01:49:53.533 --> 01:49:55.330
by the King long before Godfrey.

1244
01:49:55.402 --> 01:49:56.426
<font color="#ff80ff">(HORSE NEIGHING)</font>

1245
01:49:56.503 --> 01:49:59.301
Go back to London
and tell the King

1246
01:50:00.007 --> 01:50:03.773
that we will meet him
on a field of his choice.

1247
01:50:03.844 --> 01:50:05.209
Make way!

1248
01:50:05.279 --> 01:50:08.577
<font color="#ff80ff">BALDWIN:</font> We will not fight
to save John's crown.

1249
01:50:08.615 --> 01:50:10.879
Rather let him bend
the knee to us.

1250
01:50:11.952 --> 01:50:14.318
I'll give you more,
Sir Baldwin.

1251
01:50:15.756 --> 01:50:18.088
My breast for your sword point.

1252
01:50:19.826 --> 01:50:21.384
Use mine.

1253
01:50:25.532 --> 01:50:26.726
Go on.

1254
01:50:28.135 --> 01:50:29.466
No?

1255
01:50:29.836 --> 01:50:33.795
This is what you want, isn't it?
This is what he wants.

1256
01:50:33.874 --> 01:50:37.833
Fine, I'd rather give it to you
than have it taken by the French.

1257
01:50:38.812 --> 01:50:41.076
You mistake me, Sire.

1258
01:50:41.248 --> 01:50:45.116
I have no right and no
ambition to wear the crown.

1259
01:50:45.752 --> 01:50:48.243
But let the rightful
wearer beware.

1260
01:50:48.689 --> 01:50:52.785
From now we will be subject only
to laws that we have a hand in making.

1261
01:50:52.859 --> 01:50:57.592
We are not sheep to be made
mutton of by your butchers.

1262
01:50:57.664 --> 01:50:59.325
<font color="#ff80ff">(ALL AGREEING)</font>

1263
01:50:59.399 --> 01:51:03.062
Godfrey set himself to
turn you against me.

1264
01:51:03.136 --> 01:51:06.299
Then he did more than was
needed to accomplish that.

1265
01:51:10.877 --> 01:51:13.038
A very important decision.

1266
01:51:13.880 --> 01:51:17.475
Don't you think that we've paid
too much taxes for far too long.. .

1267
01:51:32.699 --> 01:51:35.526
<font color="#ff80ff">(YOUNG ROBIN LAUGHING)</font>

1268
01:52:25.419 --> 01:52:27.250
This is where I was born.

1269
01:52:41.401 --> 01:52:44.837
What does it mean?
It means never give up.

1270
01:52:46.306 --> 01:52:50.800
We will not be loyal to a crown
that robs and starves us!

1271
01:52:50.977 --> 01:52:54.378
The King must listen to
what we have to say!

1272
01:52:54.481 --> 01:52:59.248
A king does not bargain for the loyalty
that every subject owes him.

1273
01:52:59.519 --> 01:53:04.047
Without loyalty there is no kingdom.
There is nothing.

1274
01:53:05.525 --> 01:53:07.686
I'm here to speak for
Sir Walter Loxley.

1275
01:53:09.729 --> 01:53:11.924
Let the man speak.
Let him speak!

1276
01:53:13.033 --> 01:53:14.864
Speak! Speak!

1277
01:53:15.068 --> 01:53:17.229
Speak, if you must.

1278
01:53:18.872 --> 01:53:21.636
If you're trying to
build for the future,

1279
01:53:22.342 --> 01:53:24.867
you must set your
foundation strong.

1280
01:53:26.680 --> 01:53:31.140
The laws of this land
enslave people to its king,

1281
01:53:32.819 --> 01:53:37.085
a king who demands loyalty
but offers nothing in return.

1282
01:53:38.658 --> 01:53:41.525
I have marched from France

1283
01:53:41.595 --> 01:53:44.120
to Palestine and back.

1284
01:53:45.098 --> 01:53:46.497
And I know

1285
01:53:47.134 --> 01:53:50.262
in tyranny lies only failure.

1286
01:53:51.872 --> 01:53:54.397
You build a country
like you build a cathedral,

1287
01:53:54.474 --> 01:53:56.268
from the ground up.

1288
01:53:56.843 --> 01:53:58.970
Empower every man

1289
01:54:00.213 --> 01:54:02.113
and you will gain strength.

1290
01:54:03.984 --> 01:54:07.078
Well, who could object
to such reasonable words?

1291
01:54:09.523 --> 01:54:13.186
If Your Majesty were
to offer justice,

1292
01:54:14.427 --> 01:54:16.895
justice in the form of
a charter of liberties,

1293
01:54:17.464 --> 01:54:21.195
allowing every man to
forage for his hearth,

1294
01:54:21.868 --> 01:54:25.702
to be safe from conviction
without cause

1295
01:54:25.772 --> 01:54:27.501
or prison without charge,

1296
01:54:28.241 --> 01:54:32.507
to work, eat and live on
the sweat of his own brow

1297
01:54:33.413 --> 01:54:36.849
and be as merry as he can.. .
Sir, Godfrey's men are on to Nottingham.

1298
01:54:37.117 --> 01:54:40.018
...then that king would be great.

1299
01:54:40.520 --> 01:54:44.354
Not only would he receive
the loyalty of his people

1300
01:54:45.659 --> 01:54:47.456
but their love, as well.

1301
01:54:48.762 --> 01:54:51.287
So what would you have?

1302
01:54:51.498 --> 01:54:53.261
Castle for every man?

1303
01:54:53.333 --> 01:54:55.528
<font color="#ff80ff">(ALL SNICKERING)</font>

1304
01:54:55.602 --> 01:54:57.729
Every Englishman's home is his castle.

1305
01:54:59.172 --> 01:55:01.936
What we would ask,
Your Majesty,

1306
01:55:03.376 --> 01:55:04.843
is liberty.

1307
01:55:05.178 --> 01:55:07.305
Liberty by law!

1308
01:55:09.249 --> 01:55:11.615
Your Majesty, My Lords,

1309
01:55:12.319 --> 01:55:14.879
the French fleet is in the Channel.

1310
01:55:15.055 --> 01:55:20.049
Sire, you have a chance to
unify your subjects high and low.

1311
01:55:21.761 --> 01:55:24.052
It falls on your nod.

1312
01:55:24.231 --> 01:55:26.399
I only have to nod?

1313
01:55:30.270 --> 01:55:32.167
I can do better than that.

1314
01:55:34.474 --> 01:55:36.571
I give my word

1315
01:55:36.776 --> 01:55:39.904
that such a charter
will be written.

1316
01:55:39.980 --> 01:55:43.381
On my mother's life, l swear it.

1317
01:55:43.450 --> 01:55:46.109
<font color="#ff80ff">(ALL CHEERING)</font>

1318
01:55:48.421 --> 01:55:51.822
Godfrey makes for Nottingham.
I must stay with the King.

1319
01:55:51.891 --> 01:55:53.950
I will send Baldwin and
Fitzrobert with you.

1320
01:55:54.027 --> 01:55:57.827
We will meet again at the White
Horse when you are finished.

1321
01:55:57.897 --> 01:56:00.923
Robin, your father
was a great man.

1322
01:56:02.235 --> 01:56:04.499
And you are your father's son.

1323
01:56:15.448 --> 01:56:16.972
Maggie, who's at the house?

1324
01:56:18.652 --> 01:56:19.880
Long live the King!

1325
01:56:20.687 --> 01:56:22.745
(SCREAMING)

1326
01:56:56.156 --> 01:56:57.348
Gentlemen.

1327
01:57:05.799 --> 01:57:08.490
<font color="#ff80ff">(EXCLAIMING EXCITEDLY)</font>

1328
01:57:11.971 --> 01:57:14.464
I'm the Sheriff of Nottingham.

1329
01:57:19.145 --> 01:57:21.845
I'm French on my mother's side.

1330
01:57:25.085 --> 01:57:27.009
<font color="#ff80ff">(LAUGHING)</font>

1331
01:57:34.394 --> 01:57:36.420
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMING)</font>

1332
01:57:42.235 --> 01:57:45.136
Sir Walter! Sir Walter!

1333
01:57:53.313 --> 01:57:54.610
Loxley!

1334
01:57:54.848 --> 01:57:56.509
Show yourself!

1335
01:57:58.651 --> 01:57:59.913
Loxley!

1336
01:58:02.889 --> 01:58:04.322
Who calls here?

1337
01:58:04.824 --> 01:58:06.792
I call for Robert Loxley.

1338
01:58:07.026 --> 01:58:08.994
My son is not here
to answer you.

1339
01:58:09.095 --> 01:58:10.562
That is the truth.

1340
01:58:10.797 --> 01:58:12.628
Because he's dead in
a French ditch.

1341
01:58:14.768 --> 01:58:16.292
And who are you,
sir, to say so?

1342
01:58:18.004 --> 01:58:19.528
Who am I?

1343
01:58:28.148 --> 01:58:30.013
I'm the one who killed him.

1344
01:58:30.083 --> 01:58:31.744
<font color="#ff80ff">(SOLDIERS JEERING)</font>

1345
01:58:31.818 --> 01:58:33.547
Fight me if you dare.

1346
01:58:34.421 --> 01:58:35.854
Lord have mercy.

1347
01:58:46.299 --> 01:58:47.527
<font color="#ff80ff">(EXCLAIMING)</font>

1348
01:59:13.393 --> 01:59:15.987
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMING)</font>

1349
01:59:24.304 --> 01:59:26.329
Leave it on the table.
Leave it! Next!

1350
01:59:27.307 --> 01:59:28.968
Next! Come on!

1351
01:59:30.777 --> 01:59:32.472
Name? Loxley.

1352
01:59:32.912 --> 01:59:34.704
Christian name?

1353
01:59:34.781 --> 01:59:36.714
Marion.

1354
01:59:37.050 --> 01:59:38.745
Land?

1355
01:59:38.918 --> 01:59:40.681
5,000 acres.

1356
01:59:41.721 --> 01:59:43.450
Lady Marion Loxley?

1357
01:59:44.157 --> 01:59:45.749
I am.

1358
01:59:52.232 --> 01:59:54.429
<font color="#ff80ff">(PEOPLE CLAMORING)</font>

1359
02:00:13.620 --> 02:00:14.882
<font color="#ff80ff">(BEES BUZZING)</font>

1360
02:00:14.954 --> 02:00:18.014
Gentlemen, enjoy!

1361
02:00:20.393 --> 02:00:23.361
<font color="#ff80ff">(SOLDIERS SCREAMING)</font>

1362
02:00:51.491 --> 02:00:53.550
No one should have 4,000 acres.

1363
02:00:53.626 --> 02:00:55.651
5,000 acres.

1364
02:01:21.187 --> 02:01:22.916
<font color="#ff80ff">(INHALING)</font>

1365
02:01:25.124 --> 02:01:27.024
<font color="#ff80ff">(HAMMERING)</font>

1366
02:01:38.938 --> 02:01:41.372
<font color="#ff80ff">(SOLDIER LAUGHING)</font>

1367
02:01:42.241 --> 02:01:43.731
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMING)</font>

1368
02:02:19.579 --> 02:02:22.113
<font color="#ff80ff">(VILLAGERS SCREAMING)</font>

1369
02:02:33.893 --> 02:02:35.918
Baldwin! Fitzrobert!

1370
02:02:35.995 --> 02:02:38.589
Take the southern flank
and circle in from the west.

1371
02:02:39.098 --> 02:02:41.828
Will and Allan, get on the
rooftops and pick your targets.

1372
02:02:41.968 --> 02:02:43.458
<font color="#ff80ff">(WHISTLES)</font>

1373
02:03:03.056 --> 02:03:04.455
Lady Marion.

1374
02:03:25.945 --> 02:03:27.003
Quickly.

1375
02:03:53.372 --> 02:03:55.539
<font color="#ff80ff">MARION: </font>Follow me.

1376
02:04:13.593 --> 02:04:15.254
<font color="#ff80ff">(VILLAGERS CLAMORING)</font>

1377
02:04:15.361 --> 02:04:16.692
<font color="#ff80ff">(BABY CRYING)</font>

1378
02:04:16.763 --> 02:04:21.029
Somebody, please take the baby!
Save the baby, please!

1379
02:04:30.443 --> 02:04:32.070
John, down!

1380
02:04:38.317 --> 02:04:39.511
It's all right.

1381
02:04:39.585 --> 02:04:40.745
Go around.

1382
02:04:40.820 --> 02:04:42.082
Stand back!

1383
02:04:43.890 --> 02:04:44.948
Make way!

1384
02:04:46.058 --> 02:04:50.188
Hurry. It's all right. It's all right.
Please, hurry! Hurry!

1385
02:05:01.874 --> 02:05:02.966
Sword!

1386
02:05:22.762 --> 02:05:24.821
<font color="#ff80ff">LITTLE JOHN:</font> Get down,
you bastard French dogs!

1387
02:06:13.880 --> 02:06:15.006
<font color="#ff80ff">(PANTING)</font>

1388
02:06:15.081 --> 02:06:18.346
Where will King Philip
land and when?

1389
02:06:23.055 --> 02:06:24.955
<font color="#ff80ff">(SCREAMING)</font>

1390
02:06:32.198 --> 02:06:34.166
This is my last arrow.

1391
02:06:36.035 --> 02:06:39.698
Dungeness! Dungeness.
Two days.

1392
02:06:43.709 --> 02:06:46.234
There we have it.
We have two days.

1393
02:08:12.898 --> 02:08:16.129
Once before I said goodbye
to a man going to war.

1394
02:08:16.435 --> 02:08:18.232
He never came back.

1395
02:08:24.143 --> 02:08:25.872
Ask me nicely.

1396
02:09:00.579 --> 02:09:02.046
I love you, Marion.

1397
02:09:21.534 --> 02:09:23.465
<font color="#ff80ff">(CHANTING RHYTHMICALLY)</font>

1398
02:11:26.725 --> 02:11:28.249
<font color="#ff80ff">MARSHAL:</font> Longstride!

1399
02:11:59.191 --> 02:12:01.352
What news of Walter
and Nottingham?

1400
02:12:02.294 --> 02:12:04.888
Sir Walter is dead.
Godfrey's hand.

1401
02:12:04.964 --> 02:12:07.694
Gentlemen, we go to war.

1402
02:12:07.933 --> 02:12:11.460
It is my first time. I shall lead.

1403
02:12:11.537 --> 02:12:12.765
Forward!

1404
02:12:34.793 --> 02:12:36.886
<font color="#ff80ff">(CHANTING RHYTHMICALLY)</font>

1405
02:12:50.075 --> 02:12:52.433
<font color="#ff80ff">(YELLING)</font>

1406
02:13:09.261 --> 02:13:11.661
<font color="#ff80ff">(CHEERING)</font>

1407
02:13:52.871 --> 02:13:54.634
That's a lot of French.

1408
02:13:56.875 --> 02:13:58.967
What's to be done?

1409
02:13:59.878 --> 02:14:01.936
Archers to the cliff top.

1410
02:14:02.014 --> 02:14:04.642
Cavalry to the beach.
We'll await you there.

1411
02:14:05.050 --> 02:14:07.177
With me! Archers!

1412
02:14:09.655 --> 02:14:11.452
Excellent plan.

1413
02:14:13.726 --> 02:14:16.185
<font color="#ff80ff">(CHEERING)</font>

1414
02:14:33.145 --> 02:14:35.039
<font color="#ff80ff">MARSHAL: </font>Cavalry!

1415
02:14:46.592 --> 02:14:48.025
<font color="#ff80ff">LEAD ARCHER:</font> Ready!

1416
02:15:07.646 --> 02:15:10.376
Raise arrows! Raise arrows!

1417
02:15:11.450 --> 02:15:12.508
Ready!

1418
02:15:16.221 --> 02:15:18.121
<font color="#ff80ff">LEAD ARCHER:</font> Raise arrows!

1419
02:15:18.524 --> 02:15:20.389
Release! Release!

1420
02:15:24.096 --> 02:15:26.257
<font color="#ff80ff">(EXCLAIMING)</font>

1421
02:15:32.938 --> 02:15:34.496
Release!

1422
02:16:11.109 --> 02:16:13.137
For the love of God, Marion!

1423
02:16:16.715 --> 02:16:18.046
Loxley,

1424
02:16:18.383 --> 02:16:21.318
circle your troops and then join the charge.

1425
02:16:26.458 --> 02:16:28.150
<font color="#ff80ff">MARION: </font>With me!

1426
02:16:32.464 --> 02:16:34.161
Release!

1427
02:16:44.776 --> 02:16:45.834
Release!

1428
02:16:58.123 --> 02:17:00.489
<font color="#ff80ff">(SHOUTING)</font>

1429
02:17:33.425 --> 02:17:35.620
<font color="#ff80ff">MARION:</font> Forward!

1430
02:17:53.612 --> 02:17:55.804
<font color="#ff80ff">WILL: </font>Archers, forward!

1431
02:18:22.274 --> 02:18:24.071
Let's go, Marshal.

1432
02:18:24.142 --> 02:18:26.232
We're close enough, Sire.

1433
02:18:26.311 --> 02:18:28.142
This was not close
enough for Richard.

1434
02:18:28.213 --> 02:18:30.078
And look what happened to him.

1435
02:18:31.116 --> 02:18:32.549
Forward!

1436
02:18:33.051 --> 02:18:34.575
Protect the King!

1437
02:19:05.817 --> 02:19:07.614
This is for you, Walter.

1438
02:19:20.732 --> 02:19:23.724
No!

1439
02:19:31.009 --> 02:19:32.271
Marion!

1440
02:20:32.471 --> 02:20:34.530
<font color="#ff80ff">(YELLING)</font>

1441
02:21:15.680 --> 02:21:17.113
Marion!

1442
02:21:44.643 --> 02:21:45.871
Surrender!

1443
02:22:03.128 --> 02:22:05.891
<font color="#ff80ff">(ENGLISH SOLDIERS CHEERING)</font>

1444
02:22:08.834 --> 02:22:10.995
Sire! Sire!

1445
02:22:11.136 --> 02:22:13.195
They've surrendered, Sire!

1446
02:22:13.572 --> 02:22:15.699
Yes! To whom?

1447
02:22:19.744 --> 02:22:20.768
To him.

1448
02:22:20.846 --> 02:22:23.246
Longstride!

1449
02:22:24.416 --> 02:22:26.145
Longstride!

1450
02:22:34.192 --> 02:22:36.456
Longstride!

1451
02:22:37.562 --> 02:22:39.393
Longstride!

1452
02:23:17.302 --> 02:23:19.896
I did not make myself king.

1453
02:23:22.340 --> 02:23:23.739
God did.

1454
02:23:24.609 --> 02:23:26.634
King by divine right.

1455
02:23:26.711 --> 02:23:27.837
<font color="#ff80ff">(ALL MURMURING)</font>

1456
02:23:27.913 --> 02:23:32.078
Now you come to
me with this document

1457
02:23:32.717 --> 02:23:36.585
seeking to limit the authority
given to me by God!

1458
02:23:36.655 --> 02:23:39.180
Sire, you gave your word!

1459
02:23:39.257 --> 02:23:40.315
No.

1460
02:23:40.392 --> 02:23:44.494
Sire, you give us our word, Sire!
Did I command you to speak, sir?

1461
02:23:44.529 --> 02:23:46.827
John.. .
Or you, madam?

1462
02:23:46.898 --> 02:23:48.991
Sire, we looked to you!

1463
02:23:49.067 --> 02:23:53.098
Look to your estates, instead.

1464
02:23:55.340 --> 02:23:57.339
<font color="#ff80ff">LEAD ARCHER:</font> Archers!

1465
02:23:57.342 --> 02:24:01.570
You are fortunate that
I am in a merciful mood.

1466
02:24:01.646 --> 02:24:06.749
But as for Robin Longstride,
that mason's son,

1467
02:24:07.218 --> 02:24:11.552
for the crimes of theft and
incitement to cause unrest,

1468
02:24:11.623 --> 02:24:15.923
who pretended to be a knight of the
realm, a crime punishable by death,

1469
02:24:15.994 --> 02:24:21.731
I declare him, from this day
forth, to be an outlaw!

1470
02:24:22.834 --> 02:24:26.563
To be hunted all the
days of his life.. .

1471
02:24:26.571 --> 02:24:30.598
We will not stand for this!
.. .until his corpse, unburied, is carrion

1472
02:24:30.675 --> 02:24:34.105
for foxes and crows!

1473
02:24:36.948 --> 02:24:40.212
<font color="#ff80ff">(ALL CLAMORING)</font>

1474
02:24:56.468 --> 02:24:59.102
Hear me! Hear me!

1475
02:25:01.406 --> 02:25:03.601
By royal decree,

1476
02:25:03.675 --> 02:25:07.467
Robin Longstride, also
known as Robin of the Hood,

1477
02:25:07.479 --> 02:25:10.573
and all who shelter him or aid him

1478
02:25:10.648 --> 02:25:13.443
are declared outlaws of the realm,

1479
02:25:13.485 --> 02:25:15.180
their properties forfeit,

1480
02:25:15.253 --> 02:25:20.417
and their lives shall be taken
by any Englishman on sight.

1481
02:25:25.363 --> 02:25:28.759
A nail please? And a hammer.

1482
02:25:28.800 --> 02:25:30.428
A nail!

1483
02:26:21.019 --> 02:26:23.883
Off you go. Come on.

1484
02:26:24.222 --> 02:26:25.382
Hey, boys.

1485
02:26:25.457 --> 02:26:27.425
You've been practicing
tying your knots? Yes.

1486
02:26:27.492 --> 02:26:29.323
Have you been shooting
your bow and arrows?

1487
02:26:29.394 --> 02:26:30.986
Who hit something? Anyone?

1488
02:26:31.062 --> 02:26:33.995
The greenwood is the outlaw's friend.

1489
02:26:33.998 --> 02:26:37.628
Now, the orphan boys
make us welcome.

1490
02:26:37.635 --> 02:26:39.034
No tax, no tithe.

1491
02:26:39.104 --> 02:26:43.841
Nobody rich, nobody poor.
Fair shares for all at nature's table.

1492
02:26:43.842 --> 02:26:48.872
Many wrongs to be righted
in the country of King John.

1493
02:26:51.316 --> 02:26:53.977
Watch over us, Walter.

1494
02:29:52.997 --> 02:29:55.287
For the Lion Heart!

1495
